Marketing Campaign Analysis¶

  • Marketing Business Metrics
  • Customer Segmentation
  • A/B Testing
  • using a marketing dataset based on the data of an online subscription business to translate common business questions into measurable outcomes, including

-- "How did this campaign perform?", -- "Which channel is referring the most subscribers?", -- "Why is a particular channel underperforming?" and some more.

  • looked at Common high-level Marketing Metrics like Conversion Rate and Retention Rate.

  • segmented customers by different demographics like language, age group,... to be able to see different deeper analysis for example looking at how different marketing channels reach different age groups.

  • encoutered something went wrong in the campaign, and needed to identify the problem, which was a language mismatch, and assess the impact of the mistake.

  • run and analyzed an A/B test to check the impact of the messaging content type of the marketing emails.

Common high-level Marketing Metrics:¶

1- Conversion Rate¶

2- Retention Rate¶

1- Conversion Rate¶

Conversion Rate:¶

is the percentage of the users who saw our marketing assets and subsequently became subscribers.¶

Formula of Conversion Rate:¶

Number of people who converted / Total Number of people we marketed to¶

We can start to see the Overall Conversion Rate for the whole campagin to have a quick look to see how much was the campagin successful as a whole.¶

In [8]:
# Calculate the number of people we marketed to
total = marketing['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the number of people who subscribed
subscribers = marketing[marketing['converted'] ==True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the conversion rate
conversion_rate = subscribers/total
print(round(conversion_rate*100, 2), "%")

14.09 %

As we can see, the overall Conversion Rate for the whole campagin is 14.09 %

2- Retention Rate¶

Retention Rate :¶

is the percentage of people that remain subscribed from the users who converted to your product after a certain period of time.¶

This can give us a sense of whether our marketing campaign converted subscribers were actually interested in the product.¶

Formula of Retention Rate:¶

Number of people who remain subscribed / Total number of people who converted¶

Here,we will focus on 1-month retention. So, we need to calculate the total number of users who remain subscribers after one month.

We can start to see the Overall Retention Rate for the whole campagin to have a quick look to see how much was the campagin successful as a whole.¶

In [9]:
#calculate Retention Rate

# Calculate the number of subscribers
total_subscribers = marketing[marketing['converted']==True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the number of people who remained subscribed
retained = marketing[marketing['is_retained']==True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the retention rate
retention_rate = retained/total_subscribers
print(round(retention_rate*100, 2), "%")

676.41 %

As we can see, the overall Retention Rate for the whole campaign is 676.41 %

So how do I know if these Conversion and Retention rates are good or bad?¶

The answer is simple: it depends.¶

There is no particular number that all marketing teams are trying to reach. So, there is no Retention rate or Conversion rate that will apply across all businesses and industries. We should look at historical Conversion rates or Retention rates of companies in a similar industry to interpret our results.¶

Segmentation¶

Common ways to segment customers¶

In addition to high-level metrics, it's important to segment customers by who you're marketing to.¶

Segmenting: means breaking down metrics by specific characteristics.¶

For instance, in addition to looking at conversion rates overall, we might also want to look at conversion rate by, for example, age group or by customers' language or subscribing channel and so on.¶

It's possible that a campaign had a low conversion rate overall, but was super effective for users within specific age group for example.¶
Rather than calling the campaign a failure, we can say that our team has learned a new way to market to specific age individuals!. Then, we could use these results to conduct a campaign to market to these very specific age individuals using a different marketing technique than everyone else.¶

Now, The marketing team wants to determine how effective the campaign was on converting English speakers.¶

So, we will compare the conversion rate for English speakers to the overall conversion rate to gain a sense of how effective the marketing campaign was among this group compared to the overall population.

Then, we will compare English to the rest of the languages in the dataset. to get a sense of which languages convert well relative to others.

Aggregating Conversion Rate across time¶

Now, we will see how some of the metrics have evolved.

The marketing team wants to know whether there is any difference in the conversion rate based on "when in the month", our users saw an ad.

If we want to understand how our campaign performed, it is essential to look at how key metrics changed throughout the campaign: Key metrics can help us catch problems that may have happened during the campaign.

Metrics over time can also surface trends like gaining more subscribers over the weekends or on specific holidays.

FUNCTIONS¶

Creating and Using FUNCTIONS for effeciency¶

Creating a Conversion Rate Function¶

We can build a function to enable us to calculate conversion rate across any sub-segment we want on the fly.

So we will build a function that takes a DataFrame and list of column names and outputs the conversion rate across the column(s).

Then we test out this function.

In [21]:
# see how quickly we can calculate the conversion rate by this function instead of repetitive multiple steps.

def conversion_rate(dataframe, column_names):
    # Total number of converted users
    column_conv = dataframe[dataframe['converted']==True].groupby(column_names)['user_id'].nunique()

    # Total number users
    column_total = dataframe.groupby(column_names)['user_id'].nunique() 
    
    # Conversion rate 
    conversion_rate = column_conv/column_total
    
    # Fill missing values with 0
    conversion_rate = conversion_rate.fillna(0)
    return conversion_rate

Creating Plotting (Visualizing) Function¶

Building a function to plot the results of the conversion rate resulted from the conversion rate function.

In [23]:
# create a plotting function for visualization
def plotting_conv(dataframe):
    for column in dataframe:
        # Plot column by dataframe's index
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
        plt.plot(dataframe.index,dataframe[column])
        plt.title('Daily ' + str(column) + ' conversion rate\n', 
                  fontsize =30)
        plt.ylabel('Conversion rate', fontsize =20)
        plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize =20)
        # Show plot
        plt.show()  
        plt.clf()

Now, we can quickly generate plots for sub-segments.

Analyzing House ads conversion rate¶

We will try to identify potential causes for the decrease: If the fluctuations in metrics are due to expected shifts in user behavior (i.e., differences across the day of the week) versus a larger problem in technical implementation or marketing strategy.

We will begin by checking whether users are more likely to convert on weekends compared with weekdays and determine if that could be the cause for the changing house ads conversion rate.

A/B TESTING¶

Determining key metrics¶

The earlier you define what success looks like, the better. So, when designing the experiment, it is good to determine key success metrics.

Personalized Email V.s Generic Email¶

The focus of the following cells will be the A/B test that was run where half the emails sent were generic upsells to our product while the other half contained personalized messaging around individual usage of our site.

Comparing conversion rates (personalization & control)¶

Let's look at the conversion rate for the control and personalization.

We choose conversion rate as our key metric for this test. So, we will evaluate whether or not conversion was higher in the personalization treatment compared with the control.

Measuring the difference between the key metric in the control and the treatment is the most important part of evaluating the success of an A/B test.

We can see that personalization converted users at a higher rate than the control. The question now is by how much.

So, we will build a lift function to quantify by how much.

Calculating "Lift" to quantify by how much the conversion rate higher for the treatment¶

  • What's the lift?

In this situation, it means "Was the conversion rate higher for the treatment and by how much?".

Lift is calculated by taking the difference between the treatment conversion rate and the control conversion rate divided by the control conversion rate.

The result is the relative percent difference of treatment compared to control.

The formula of calculating lift:

(Treatment Conversion Rate - Control Conversion Rate) / Control Conversion Rate

In [38]:
# Creating a lift function
# create a function to automate the process of calculating lift.

def lift(a,b):
    # Calcuate the mean of a and b
    a_mean = np.mean(a)
    b_mean = np.mean(b)
    
    # Calculate the lift using a_mean and b_mean
    lift = (b_mean-a_mean)/a_mean
  
    return str(round(lift*100, 2)) + '%'
  
# Print lift() with control and personalization as inputs
print(lift(control, personalization))

38.85%

As we can see, there's a large lift. The personalization variant improved on the control conversion rate by 38.85%. That's a huge improvement and a very good signal that we should consider running personalized emails again in the future.

But are our results statistically significant?

It's time for us to determine whether the result is statistically significant.

Statistical significance is vital to understanding whether a test showed a positive result by chance or if it is reflective of a true difference between the variants. This will enable the marketing team to make an informed choice about whether to roll out the feature or not.

  • T-distribution

One way to calculate statistical significance is by conducting a two-sample t-test.

A t-test uses the mean and the sample variance to determine the likelihood that the variation between the two samples occurred by chance.

  • P-value The t-test gives us a t-statistic and a p-value

Remember, a p-value less than 0.05 is typically considered statistically significant at 95% significance level.

In [39]:
# Evaluating statistical significance

# using the ttest_ind() function from the stats module of the scipy package. The function takes a list of outcomes for each 
#variant. In this case, the "outcomes" are whether or not each user converted. Using control and personalization as the inputs.
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
ttest_ind(control, personalization)
Out[39]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-2.7343299447505074, pvalue=0.006451487844694175)

Is the difference between the control and personalization statistically significant?

Yes, the results are statistically significant with p = 0.006. The personalization results are highly statistically significant.

Since the p-value here is indeed less than 0.05, we can be confident that the difference in conversion rates is statistically significant.

We should explore whether that holds up across all demographics.¶

A/B Testing & Segmentation¶

One of the most common pitfalls in A/B testing is assuming that a treatment equally affects everyone in a population.

Segmentation! (Not all customers are alike!)¶

Just like with any other kind of marketing, some treatments are particularly effective on users of a specific engagement level, age, race, or any other factor and these treatments may not be effective for other users as well.

Often a treatment will not affect all people uniformly. Some people will love a particular marketing campaign while others hate it. The marketing team has to target users according to their preferences.

So, it is important to break down results by various demographics in order to obtain an understanding of the impact of the test.

Creating an A/B test segmenting function¶

Since we want to segment our data multiple times, we will build a function ab_segmentation() that analyzes the impact of our A/B tests on segments of data that we can reuse in this kind of analysis.

In [40]:
# The function takes in a column name and run through each unique value in that column 
# calculating lift and statistical significance.


def ab_segmentation(segment):
  #for loop for each subsegment in marketing  to calculate lift and statistical significance across multiple segments of users.

  for subsegment in np.unique(marketing[segment].values):
        print(subsegment)
      
      # Limit marketing to email and subsegment
        email = marketing[(marketing['marketing_channel'] == 'Email') & (marketing[segment] == subsegment)]

        subscribers = email.groupby(['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max()
        subscribers = pd.DataFrame(subscribers.unstack(level=1)) 
        control = subscribers['control'].dropna()
        personalization = subscribers['personalization'].dropna()

        print('lift:', lift(control, personalization)) 
        print('t-statistic:', ttest_ind(control, personalization), '\n\n')
